treatmentWhy: I chose these pain options based off the process of elimination. And based off of just one symptom I cannot recommend a surgical procedure without more information. Tier 3 and Tier 2 includes different opiates, and I would definitely not recommend this to a patient that I haven't seen or to one that does not absolutely require them. This is because the potential for addiction is so high. I would start with Tier 1, the most minimally invasive and lowest threat option and see if it helps to alleviate the symptoms. If it doesn't then we can ask about more potential symptoms and think of other treatment options, like possibly the higher tiers. For now, I'm hoping the topical lidocane and acetaminophin will help enough. Also, doctors can prescribe high levels of acetaminophen for pain that are higher levels than can be found OTC but are still safe and effective.

treatmentWhy: When possible and appropriate, starting with more conservative treatment for low back pain is advisable. It appears this is a young relatively healthy patient whom the doctor is seeing for the first time. Without more history provided, we can't know if the patient has a substance use disorder or some other contraindications to opioids. Pluse, opioids do have significant risks. For most patients with low back pain, authoritative bodies recommend starting therapy with nonpharmacologic interventions (i.e. exercise, physical therapy) and nonopioid treatments (i.e. NSAIDs when not contraindicated). Thus, from the options provided, tylenol and the topical lidocaine were selected for safer alternatives to opioids for this patient.
notes:
'-Patient presents with left sided low back pain, subacute.
-Patient says they have not had improvement in sx.
-Topical lidocaine patch and epidural steroids recommended as initial conservative pharmacologic therapy 
-Nonpharmacologic interventions for LBP management also advised (ie Physical Therapy referral, Exercise such as walking/swimming, Mind-Body activities such as yoga or tai chi)
-Patient advised to try their best with the advised treatment plan for 4 to 6 weeks, follow up appointment in about 6 weeks, sooner if sx worsen, and to contact office with any questions or concerns as needed

moveForwardOpen: Ask if they would be willing to share if there were other circumstances in their life that could be impacting their health or their ability to follow the recommended treatments at this time in order to determine best how to help them.
treatmentWhy: The patient had noted that they were busy and hadn't really been able to comply with the therapies recommended at the prior visit. As the treating physician, I would want to understand more about the patient's pain and why they didn't follow through with the previously recommended treatment so that I could best help them. For example, were they unable to get the scripts filled due to an insurance coverage issue, did they have an adverse reaction to the medicine and discontinued use, etc. It's advisable to give more conservative treatments a concerted effort (perhaps for 4 to 6 weeks) before moving onto more invasive testing/procedures or stronger (perhaps riskier) medications. The lidocaine topical patch should be relatively safe and easy to use. The steroid injection may provide longer pain relief and help decrease inflammation.
notes:

-Patient states they have not had improvement in sx.
